        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022404994900094\">Carboni–Johnson–Street–Verity's _Modulated Bicategories_</a> one finds the following:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/1Fb6T118am6nMDpzI9u8PgcP/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/1Fb6T118am6nMDpzI9u8PgcP/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/1Fb6T118am6nMDpzI9u8PgcP/image.png\"></a></div><p>Here \"pseudopullback\" actually means \"isocomma object\".</p>\n<p>I wanted to confirm two basic/elementary questions I have:</p>\n<p>1) Are pseudoepic morphisms the ones such that the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/epimorphism#BasicCharacterizationOfEpimorphisms\">analogous diagram as the above one</a> is an \"isococomma\" square?<br>\n2) Is \"opcomma object\" the same thing as a \"cocomma object\"? The former is <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1902.01225.pdf#page=11\">described e.g. here</a> or in Street's Elementary Cosmoi I paper, while the later (specialised to the 2-category of categories) is described <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/247280/an-explicit-description-of-cocomma-categories\">here</a></p>",
        "id": 430892850,
        "sender_full_name": "Emily",
        "timestamp": 1712101325
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Uh never heard of opcommas. Do you think you can explain the difference between them and cocommas?</p>",
        "id": 430933609,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712128537
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276871\">Emily</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/isococomma.20squares.20and.20pseudoepic.20morphisms/near/430892850\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>2) Is \"opcomma object\" the same thing as a \"cocomma object\"? The former is <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1902.01225.pdf#page=11\">described e.g. here</a> or in Street's Elementary Cosmoi I paper, while the later (specialised to the 2-category of categories) is described <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/247280/an-explicit-description-of-cocomma-categories\">here</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The terms \"cocomma\" and \"opcomma\" and \"cospan\" and \"opspan\" are used interchangeably in the 2-category literature, as far as I can tell. There is an unfortunate tension between the convention for duality in a 1-category, in which an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mtext>op</mtext></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathscr C^{\\text{op}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.1689em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is called a \"co-<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>\" in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathscr C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.1689em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, and the convention for duality in a 2-category, in which there are two notions of dual, \"op\" and \"co\". It would make most sense to use the \"op-\" prefix for \"op\" and the \"co-\" prefix for \"co\", and this does recover the duality between monads and comonads, for instance. However, this choice conflicts with the terminology with 1-categories, meaning that one would call the categorification of a coproduct in a 1-category an \"op-product\" in a 2-category. (Arguably it is the convention for 1-categories that is bad, but it's not viable to change this now.) So different authors have chosen different conventions for 2-categories. Usually categorifications of 1-dimensional (co)limits use the \"co-\" prefix, whilst truly 2-dimensional (co)limits often use the \"op-\" prefix. But it really depends on the author, and there may be instances in the literature where neither of these conventions have been followed.</p>",
        "id": 430940085,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1712131039
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My impression is that \"cocomma\" is much more common in recent papers.  If I saw \"opcomma\" I might expect it to mean a comma object in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^{\\mathrm{co}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">co</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, just as an opfibration is a fibration in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^{\\mathrm{co}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">co</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 431111482,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1712155817
    },
